<p><b>Lesotho</b> (pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/lɨˈsuːtuː/</a></span><small>&#160;(<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media:Lesotho.ogg" title="Media:Lesotho.ogg"><img alt="Speaker Icon.svg" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Speaker_Icon.svg/13px-Speaker_Icon.svg.png" width="13" height="13" /></a> <a href="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/79/Lesotho.ogg" class="internal" title="Lesotho.ogg">listen</a>)</small>), officially the <b>Kingdom of Lesotho</b>, is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landlocked" title="Landlocked" class="mw-redirect">landlocked</a> country and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enclave" title="Enclave" class="mw-redirect">enclave</a> — entirely surrounded by the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">Republic of South Africa</a>. It is just over 30,000&#160;km² in size with an estimated population of almost	1,800,000. Its capital and largest city is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maseru" title="Maseru">Maseru</a>. Lesotho is the southernmost landlocked country in the world. It is a member of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commonwealth_of_Nations" title="Commonwealth of Nations">Commonwealth of Nations</a>. The name "Lesotho" translates roughly into "the land of the people who speak <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sesotho_language" title="Sesotho language" class="mw-redirect">Sesotho</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lesotho#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> About 40% of the population live below the international poverty line of US$1.25 a day.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lesotho#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
